            "html": "<p class=\"q-text qu-display--block\" style=\"box-sizing: border-box; margin-bottom: 1em; overflow-wrap: anywhere; word-break: break-word; direction: ltr; text-align: start;\"><span style=\"font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; background: none;\">There’s an excellent book series, “Culture Shock . . . . . . .”. Look for the one on France as the series is about COUNTRIES, not specific cities. Call ALLIANCE FRANCAIS, the best language institute in the world for Learning French. Ask your questions. they’ll be able to answer them and tell you a lot of other things.</span></p> <p class=\"q-text qu-display--block\" style=\"box-sizing: border-box; margin-bottom: 1em; overflow-wrap: anywhere; word-break: break-word; direction: ltr; text-align: start;\"><span style=\"font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; background: none;\">LAWS ? The only one that might be different from the laws in your country (the US I’m guessing), is that you MUST have ID on you at all times as the police can ask you for it. This happened to me years ago in a crush of people in the Metro at rush hour. I laughed and said, “What? Are you the SS or Something?” Not funny. I said I didn’t know that I was supposed to carry some form of ID, and when they said why not your passport, I replied that I never carried it for fear of being robbed. They didn’t guillotine me, but it was close. And I’m not joking. LANGUAGE. Learn some French !! At the very least, when you enter a small shop, be sure to greet the salesperson by saying “Bonjour MADAME (or Monsieur).” Just “Bonjour” is considered rude. Say the same as you leave (“Aurevoir Madame—or Monsieur).</span></p> <p class=\"q-text qu-display--block\" style=\"box-sizing: border-box; margin-bottom: 0px; overflow-wrap: anywhere; word-break: break-word; direction: ltr; text-align: start;\"><span style=\"font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; background: none;\">Get the INSIGHT GUIDE to Paris—tons of wonderful explanations, or google major sights. CUSTOMS 14 July is france’s National Day—In Canada and the US we cal it Bastille Day —look up the history of 14 July 1789—beginning of the French Revolution. Here in France, we call it “La Fête Nationale” the national celebration or feast day ! Another custom is the kiss on either cheek—people who know each other INCLUDING 2 men. No, they’re NOT GAY !!! Again, the book, Culture Shock France will tell you a lot about customs and do’s and dont’s. TRAVEL HACKS are common in the bars around the Moulin Rouge and Lido (Montmartre. You want a lass of wine, they don’t sell by the glass, just by the bottle. Ok, you think, and the bottle arrives and a glass is poured for you. Too late you realise you’ve been took—the bottle costs a fortune—$100 or more. don’t have a drink there or anywhere very close to a major tourist site. Walk away a few streets, and the price will go down a bit. FOOD. The Glory of France and taken VERY VERY seriously. Eat your main meal at lunch and it will be cheaper than the same at dinner (usually). Eat Kebabs and even burgers or sandwiches you make from a baguette, some ham and cheese. DO NOT ask for your beef well-done. It’s simply NOT DONE!! and they’ll put you in the category “ugly ignorant American.” Same same about DRESS. Parisians wear jeans and sneakers, but still manage to look elegant—add a scarf, roll the Bottom of the jeans up a bit. People-Watch like mad and you’ll soon be able to figure out how the French look so chic and elegant—and it doesn’t have to cost more than Zara or H and M; Have a great stay ! If you’re like I was at 21, you’ll never want to</span></p> ",
